11:47.498 --> 11:49.584
You only have an hour left.

11:49.584 --> 11:51.377
- It's so close.

11:51.377 --> 11:53.171
<i>I still need</i>
<i>to get this warp out.</i>

11:53.171 --> 11:55.465
Come on, little knife.

11:55.465 --> 11:59.385
Back into the forge, and I just
use my little ball-peen hammer

11:59.385 --> 12:03.056
<i>to straighten out the warp</i>
<i>with a very low heat.</i>

12:03.056 --> 12:06.976
<i>My blade is straight, and it's</i>
<i>just beautiful. I love that.</i>

12:06.976 --> 12:10.146
- Brad has actually got
a very narrow blade.

12:10.146 --> 12:12.315
- It's a breadknife.

12:12.315 --> 12:14.609
<i>- Hopefully the judges</i>
<i>like an original blade.</i>

12:14.609 --> 12:18.279
The world's first
Japanese hoof slicer.

12:18.279 --> 12:21.449
- I'm severely cramping
in my hands.

12:21.449 --> 12:24.285
It's 87 degrees, humid,

12:24.285 --> 12:26.537
sun's on top of me.

12:26.537 --> 12:28.873
I can't even think straight
right now.

12:28.873 --> 12:30.959
<i>It's impossible for me to tell</i>
<i>if this blade got up</i>

12:30.959 --> 12:33.628
to quenching temperature
in this sun.

12:33.628 --> 12:35.922
I just look for color
and quench it.

12:35.922 --> 12:38.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:38.633 --> 12:40.927
No cracks.
I'm happy with that.

12:40.927 --> 12:43.554
- Starting a new mantra.

12:43.554 --> 12:47.433
Don't let the perfect
be the enemy of the good enough.

12:47.433 --> 12:50.353
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:50.353 --> 12:53.189
- Brendan's getting
the quench now.

12:53.189 --> 12:54.607
- This is the scary part, guys.

12:54.607 --> 12:56.818
My blade's nice and straight.

12:56.818 --> 13:00.446
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:00.446 --> 13:02.448
[bleep].

13:02.448 --> 13:04.659
There's a great big
old speed hole in my knife.

13:04.659 --> 13:06.494
I'm nervous
about this inclusion.

13:06.494 --> 13:09.539
<i>I'm sure people have</i>
<i>gone home for far less,</i>

13:09.539 --> 13:11.624
<i>but I don't have time</i>
<i>to start over.</i>

13:11.624 --> 13:15.169
This is it. I got to make it
sharp at least.

13:15.169 --> 13:19.382
- Ten, nine, eight, seven,

13:19.382 --> 13:22.427
six, five, four,

13:22.427 --> 13:25.513
three, two, one.

13:25.513 --> 13:27.932
Bladesmiths,
this round is over.

13:27.932 --> 13:31.394
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:31.394 --> 13:35.565
- My arms have never cramped
this bad in my life, ever,

13:35.565 --> 13:37.275
<i>and I'm concerned the judges</i>

13:37.275 --> 13:40.403
might think my blade
is a little thick.

13:40.403 --> 13:42.155
- Bladesmiths, that was

13:42.155 --> 13:45.116
a very challenging
round of competition.

13:45.116 --> 13:48.411
Now it's time for the judges to
take a closer look at your work.

13:48.411 --> 13:49.996
Brad, you're up first.

13:51.914 --> 13:54.083
- Well, Brad,
for a narrow blade,

13:54.083 --> 13:57.045
there's enough spine on there
to give this some weight to it.

13:57.045 --> 13:58.880
Look forward to seeing a
little development on the handle

13:58.880 --> 14:00.631
if this goes forward.

14:00.631 --> 14:03.051
It's a little bit square,
kind of blocky,

14:03.051 --> 14:05.386
but other than that, good job.

14:05.386 --> 14:07.013
- Brendan, you're up next.

14:07.013 --> 14:09.015
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:09.015 --> 14:11.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:11.392 --> 14:14.312
- It's nice and straight, and
it's got a good weight to it,

14:14.312 --> 14:16.481
but the 80-pound gorilla
in the room is the void

14:16.481 --> 14:18.566
that was in the steel
that you picked.

14:18.566 --> 14:19.776
- I'm not sure where you're
going with your handle.

14:19.776 --> 14:21.652
It gets very thin there.

14:21.652 --> 14:24.197
That finger well kind of
is in the wrong place.

14:24.197 --> 14:27.283
You know, it's not lined up
with the rest of my hand.

14:27.283 --> 14:29.368
- Jeff, you're up next.

14:29.368 --> 14:30.995
Please present
your work to the judges.

14:32.622 --> 14:35.625
- Turned in a blade
with a really nice profile.

14:35.625 --> 14:37.376
If you were to get
to the next round,

14:37.376 --> 14:40.088
I would certainly say
take some mass out of it.

14:40.088 --> 14:42.507
- There is that issue
of a big handle.

14:42.507 --> 14:45.384
I can feel it cutting into my
hand right now, so refine that.

14:45.384 --> 14:48.054
But it is a good looking shape.
Good job.

14:48.054 --> 14:50.723
- Thank you.
- All right, Wes, you're up.

14:50.723 --> 14:52.350
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:54.644 --> 14:56.896
- The big concern is, I mean,

14:56.896 --> 15:00.525
there are five major,
visible cracks,

15:00.525 --> 15:05.113
one of which runs almost 3/4
of an inch up into that blade.

15:05.113 --> 15:07.073
The fact that you do have
a lot of blade

15:07.073 --> 15:11.160
beyond that could be
your saving grace.

15:11.160 --> 15:14.497
- Well, bladesmiths, the judges
have to make a final decision,

15:14.497 --> 15:15.873
so while they do that,
I'm gonna ask you

15:15.873 --> 15:17.083
to leave your blades here

15:17.083 --> 15:19.001
and step off the Forge floor.

15:19.001 --> 15:20.378
Thank you.

15:20.378 --> 15:24.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:24.090 --> 15:27.301
- That was rough. I think that
was harder than blacksmithing.

15:27.301 --> 15:29.637
- We're gonna start
with Brad's knife right here.

15:29.637 --> 15:30.555
- Oh, man.

15:32.390 --> 15:36.644
- Brad's blade is perfectly
straight. It's nice and clean.

15:36.644 --> 15:38.688
The handle itself
is gonna need some work.

15:38.688 --> 15:41.482
I'm really nervous about
the heat treat that he did.

15:41.482 --> 15:43.526
Let's see what we got here.

15:43.526 --> 15:45.987
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:45.987 --> 15:48.614
I mean, it's marginal.

15:48.614 --> 15:51.826
- Let's move on to our next
bladesmith, Brendan.

15:51.826 --> 15:54.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:54.162 --> 15:56.455
<i>- The issue I have with this</i>
<i>knife is it just happened.</i>

15:56.455 --> 15:59.792
This is less designed
and more haphazard.

15:59.792 --> 16:02.336
This void here,
it feels like a pocket,

16:02.336 --> 16:05.298
but it doesn't feel like it goes
too far back into the blade,

16:05.298 --> 16:07.842
which is a good thing.

16:07.842 --> 16:12.305
- I'm a little nervous that some
of this blade is not hardened.

16:12.305 --> 16:15.183
Yeah.
That is not hardened.

16:15.183 --> 16:16.934
- Are you gonna grind it
a lot more,

16:16.934 --> 16:18.978
or are you gonna try to
keep the weight on?

16:18.978 --> 16:21.355
- I don't know if I'm gonna have
the opportunity to grind it.

16:21.355 --> 16:25.401
- Okay, let's move on to our
next smith, and that is Jeff.

16:25.401 --> 16:27.862
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:27.862 --> 16:30.448
- He did have his own
inexperience with coal forges,

16:30.448 --> 16:32.575
but he didn't let
that defeat him.

16:32.575 --> 16:34.660
As you can see,
there are no visible cracks.

16:34.660 --> 16:38.206
We're worried about if he were
just cold hammering that.

16:38.206 --> 16:39.749
- I was a little nervous about
if he got it

16:39.749 --> 16:42.084
hot enough in the forge.

16:42.084 --> 16:45.671
Oh, yeah. That's nice.
It skates right off.

16:45.671 --> 16:49.050
- And our last bladesmith.
Let's move on to Wes.

16:49.050 --> 16:50.843
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:50.843 --> 16:52.803
<i>- Any time you hit steel</i>
<i>when it's cold,</i>

16:52.803 --> 16:54.972
you're running a risk of putting
stress fractures in it.

16:54.972 --> 16:57.892
That crack comes up to here,
at least,

16:57.892 --> 16:59.936
and that one comes up to here.

16:59.936 --> 17:02.104
So at this point,

17:02.104 --> 17:04.065
he's gonna need to lose
almost an inch of blade

17:04.065 --> 17:05.483
to get out of that crack.

17:05.483 --> 17:07.151
Is it salvageable? Yes.

17:07.151 --> 17:11.072
Is it risky? Yeah.
Way over the top.

17:11.072 --> 17:13.532
- Let's check the hardness
of this here.

17:13.532 --> 17:15.826
Oh, yeah.

17:15.826 --> 17:18.037
It's the hardest one there.

17:18.037 --> 17:19.830
- So, Doug, have you made
your final decision?

17:19.830 --> 17:20.998
- Yes, I have.

17:20.998 --> 17:21.999
- Dave?
- Yeah.

17:21.999 --> 17:23.542
- Ben?
- Yes.

17:23.542 --> 17:26.128
- All right.
Let's go tell our smiths.

17:26.128 --> 17:28.923
Bladesmiths, the judges
have evaluated your work,

17:28.923 --> 17:30.883
and they've made
their final decision.

17:30.883 --> 17:32.927
The bladesmith leaving
the Forge is...

17:32.927 --> 17:37.682
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:37.682 --> 17:39.058
Wes.

17:39.058 --> 17:40.810
Your blade did not make the cut.

17:40.810 --> 17:43.437
- Wes, I really like the shape
your knife took,

17:43.437 --> 17:45.273
and I was really impressed
with your hammer work,

17:45.273 --> 17:46.607
drawing that point out
without putting any folds

17:46.607 --> 17:48.818
in that material.

17:48.818 --> 17:50.820
But eventually, you wound up
with those stress fractures,

17:50.820 --> 17:53.281
and whether they came from
the hammer blows on cold metal

17:53.281 --> 17:55.366
or from the quench,
we can't really tell,

17:55.366 --> 17:58.452
but there are enough of them
that we've got to let you go.

17:58.452 --> 18:01.414
- Wes, please surrender
your blade.

18:01.414 --> 18:04.125
<i>- I'll always be grateful</i>
<i>for the opportunity.</i>

18:04.125 --> 18:05.793
<i>I'm not the kind of person</i>

18:05.793 --> 18:07.628
<i>that gives up after</i>
<i>falling down.</i>

18:07.628 --> 18:12.341
I've faced bears and men
with guns, four divorces.

18:12.341 --> 18:14.552
[laughs]

18:14.552 --> 18:17.346
<i>Forging is what I do,</i>
<i>and I'm gonna keep doing it.</i>

18:19.390 --> 18:21.475
- Congratulations, bladesmiths.

18:21.475 --> 18:23.477
You've made it to the second
round of this competition,

18:23.477 --> 18:25.313
and now that your blades
have been tempered,

18:25.313 --> 18:27.106
it's time to turn them into
fully functional weapons

18:27.106 --> 18:28.983
by attaching handles to them.

18:28.983 --> 18:32.987
However, we've got
the added enjoyment of

18:32.987 --> 18:36.991
<i>including a hidden lanyard hole</i>
<i>in your tang design.</i>

18:36.991 --> 18:39.118
When the time runs out,

18:39.118 --> 18:41.078
your weapons will be tested
for strength and durability

18:41.078 --> 18:43.039
in a hoof chop

18:43.039 --> 18:46.042
and for sharpness
in a burlap bag slice.

18:46.042 --> 18:47.793
Good luck, bladesmiths.

18:47.793 --> 18:49.754
Your three hours starts now.

18:49.754 --> 18:52.465
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:52.465 --> 18:55.635
Let's talk a little bit about
this recessed lanyard hole.

18:55.635 --> 18:57.470
- The one thing I'm nervous
about is that these guys

18:57.470 --> 18:59.221
are gonna get into a focus,

18:59.221 --> 19:00.473
and they're gonna get
their glue on there,

19:00.473 --> 19:02.308
they're gonna put their pins,

19:02.308 --> 19:05.019
and forget to give a little
hollow for that lanyard.

19:05.019 --> 19:08.564
- [chuckles]
Welding.

19:08.564 --> 19:10.691
<i>The first thing</i>
<i>I have to do in this round</i>

19:10.691 --> 19:14.779
is fix this void by adding
material without heating it up,

19:14.779 --> 19:17.823
but you can't do one
without the other.

19:17.823 --> 19:20.785
If I apply too much heat
while welding this void,

19:20.785 --> 19:23.079
<i>it's gonna ruin the temper.</i>

19:23.079 --> 19:25.414
- Oh, don't, no.

19:25.414 --> 19:28.209
It's really easy to want to
dual off that weld quickly,

19:28.209 --> 19:30.670
and what you wind up with
is a weld that's solid,

19:30.670 --> 19:32.213
but the metal on either
side of that weld is now

19:32.213 --> 19:33.673
brutal as heck.

19:33.673 --> 19:36.008
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:36.008 --> 19:38.010
<i>- Dave doesn't like the way</i>
<i>this fits in his hand.</i>

19:38.010 --> 19:40.137
<i>It's the weakest part</i>
<i>on the blade.</i>

19:40.137 --> 19:42.765
I can only remove so much
without it just snapping,

19:42.765 --> 19:44.308
flying across the room,

19:44.308 --> 19:46.310
and then it's back
to square one,

19:46.310 --> 19:48.270
<i>and square one will be me</i>
<i>scratching my head</i>

19:48.270 --> 19:50.398
<i>in my own shop,</i>

19:50.398 --> 19:52.608
reliving this event
over and over again.

19:52.608 --> 19:54.610
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:54.610 --> 19:56.696
- Putting a hidden lanyard
hole in the handle

19:56.696 --> 19:59.115
is gonna be no problem at all,

19:59.115 --> 20:01.826
<i>but I feel like three hours</i>
<i>is not enough time for me</i>

20:01.826 --> 20:06.205
to finish the 500 things
I have to do.

20:06.205 --> 20:10.376
My biggest worry is
there's no transition

20:10.376 --> 20:12.878
between my blade and the handle.

20:12.878 --> 20:17.049
I really need to resolve that,
so I'm adding a guard.

20:17.049 --> 20:21.011
- An unprompted guard? Has that
ever happened here in the Forge?

20:22.096 --> 20:24.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:24.140 --> 20:25.933
<i>- I've never done a hidden</i>
<i>lanyard hole,</i>

20:25.933 --> 20:28.310
but anything's easier
than a coal forge.

20:28.310 --> 20:30.062
<i>I chose G10 for the handle,</i>

20:30.062 --> 20:32.940
and I'm gonna do
a little razzle dazzle.

20:32.940 --> 20:35.067
<i>This handle</i>
<i>is gonna be beautiful.</i>

20:35.067 --> 20:38.112
- Your cutouts on your handle
material should curve,

20:38.112 --> 20:39.613
match up with the back end
of the hole...

20:39.613 --> 20:41.490
- Right.
- And then curve out again,

20:41.490 --> 20:42.700
so when you push
the lanyard through,

20:42.700 --> 20:44.577
it just slides through the hole.

20:44.577 --> 20:47.455
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:47.455 --> 20:49.039
- I'm grinding away
at the grinder.

20:49.039 --> 20:51.375
<i>I'm taking as much meat</i>
<i>and handle off,</i>

20:51.375 --> 20:54.044
<i>because that's exactly</i>
<i>what they told me to do.</i>

20:54.044 --> 20:56.756
But to do a good hoof chop,

20:56.756 --> 20:58.758
<i>you want a little meat</i>
<i>on your blade,</i>

20:58.758 --> 21:02.762
so I'm gonna leave mine a little
thicker than the other guys.

21:02.762 --> 21:04.680
You get a little
advantage there.

21:04.680 --> 21:06.807
- Brendan has grabbed
some handle material.

21:06.807 --> 21:09.351
It looks like 1/4-inch Micarta.

21:09.351 --> 21:11.103
<i>- This piece looks like</i>
<i>it's gonna be</i>

21:11.103 --> 21:13.147
<i>just the right thickness.</i>

21:13.147 --> 21:14.940
I won't have to
take away that much,

21:14.940 --> 21:16.776
and then I got to put nice
little hidden pockets

21:16.776 --> 21:18.736
so you can put a lanyard
through that lanyard hole.

21:18.736 --> 21:21.739
And what I'm doing
is using the natural radius

21:21.739 --> 21:24.408
of this grinding belt wheel,

21:24.408 --> 21:27.953
get the router out--
sweet little pocket.

21:27.953 --> 21:29.705
- Yeah, the one thing I hope is
that that lanyard hole

21:29.705 --> 21:31.832
should be bigger than 1/4 inch.

21:31.832 --> 21:33.626
- There's nothing worse
than having a lanyard hole

21:33.626 --> 21:36.295
that's really tough
to get a lanyard into.

21:36.295 --> 21:39.882
- That ain't bad.
I like it.

21:39.882 --> 21:44.386
- You have 60 minutes.
That's 60 minutes remaining.

21:44.386 --> 21:46.514
<i>- One of my favorite things</i>
<i>to do with knives</i>

21:46.514 --> 21:49.391
<i>is making the handles,</i>

21:49.391 --> 21:51.185
but I've never worked
with five-minute epoxy.

21:51.185 --> 21:54.897
Those are small gloves.

21:54.897 --> 21:58.442
I can't stand
having glue on my skin.

21:58.442 --> 22:00.945
- So Brad, I noticed,
one of his scales is, like,

22:00.945 --> 22:02.863
1 1/2 times thicker
than the other one.

22:02.863 --> 22:05.074
- Yeah.

22:05.074 --> 22:07.660
I have a feeling that Brad's
gonna give us the blocky handle.

22:07.660 --> 22:11.455
<i>- I glue the handle on,</i>
<i>and the holes don't line up.</i>

22:11.455 --> 22:14.208
I wasn't expecting that.

22:14.208 --> 22:15.584
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:15.584 --> 22:17.211
<i>The epoxy's getting hard.</i>

22:17.211 --> 22:19.713
- This could be a disaster.

22:19.713 --> 22:22.466
<i>- I'm not sure I could get</i>
<i>the pins in there.</i>

22:22.466 --> 22:26.470
<i>With one hour left,</i>
<i>if I'd have to redo my handle,</i>

22:26.470 --> 22:28.472
<i>I'm going home.</i>

22:28.472 --> 22:29.431
Ahh!

22:31.725 --> 22:34.603
I realized I just grabbed
the wrong side's scale.

22:34.603 --> 22:39.233
<i>Good thing I realized that</i>
<i>before the epoxy set.</i>

22:39.233 --> 22:42.278
<i>It went together fairly well,</i>
<i>but it's crazy.</i>

22:42.278 --> 22:44.530
There's just not much time left.

22:44.530 --> 22:46.407
<i>I'm usually relaxed at home</i>

22:46.407 --> 22:49.159
<i>doing all this,</i>
<i>with some music playing.</i>

22:49.159 --> 22:51.954
I feel like the clock,
it's just killing me.

22:51.954 --> 22:53.914
- Bladesmiths!

22:53.914 --> 22:57.459
There are only 30 minutes
left on that clock.

22:57.459 --> 22:59.628
- I made it past the coal forge.

22:59.628 --> 23:01.547
That was hell.

23:01.547 --> 23:02.590
<i>This second round,</i>
<i>and even making it here,</i>

23:02.590 --> 23:04.341
<i>I'm in heaven.</i>

23:04.341 --> 23:06.093
<i>I'm enjoying every minute</i>
<i>of it.</i>

23:06.093 --> 23:08.304
Might not look like it,
but I'm smiling.

23:08.304 --> 23:10.472
- It looks like he's kind
of going with that napped look

23:10.472 --> 23:11.682
where you put a lot
of little dents and grooves

23:11.682 --> 23:13.726
all over everything.

23:13.726 --> 23:15.936
Done right, it can be
a pretty comfortable handle;

23:15.936 --> 23:19.315
done wrong, it's just a million
hot spots throughout your palm.

23:19.315 --> 23:21.483
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:21.483 --> 23:24.153
<i>- I fixed everything</i>
<i>the judges wanted me to fix,</i>

23:24.153 --> 23:26.697
and I'm just going to town.
I'm just cruising along.

23:26.697 --> 23:28.782
- It still looks like
a really beefy knife.

23:28.782 --> 23:31.160
- He seems to like
the heft of it.

23:31.160 --> 23:32.202
- But people also think
their babies are cute

23:32.202 --> 23:33.829
when they're not.

23:33.829 --> 23:35.998
[laughter]

23:35.998 --> 23:38.000
<i>- I think I've got the best</i>
<i>blade going in so far,</i>

23:38.000 --> 23:40.836
<i>so I think I'm going home...</i>

23:40.836 --> 23:42.922
to the final round.

23:42.922 --> 23:45.841
- Ten, nine, eight,

23:45.841 --> 23:49.178
seven, six, five,

23:49.178 --> 23:53.390
four, three, two, one.

23:53.390 --> 23:58.145
Bladesmiths, drop your tools.
This round is over.

23:58.145 --> 24:00.522
- I'm confident that I fixed
the issues

24:00.522 --> 24:02.608
<i>the judges had with my knife,</i>

24:02.608 --> 24:04.526
<i>but Jeff's handle</i>
<i>looks pretty sparkly.</i>

24:04.526 --> 24:07.446
I don't know.
Maybe he is Magic Mike.

24:08.906 --> 24:11.909
- Bladesmiths, this is the
strength test: the hoof chop.

24:11.909 --> 24:14.453
I'm gonna be chopping into
these hooves ten times,

24:14.453 --> 24:16.914
and remember, this isn't about
what happens to the hooves;

24:16.914 --> 24:19.124
this is what the hooves
do to your blades.

24:19.124 --> 24:20.417
Brad, you're up first.
You ready?

24:20.417 --> 24:22.169
- I am ready.

24:22.169 --> 24:25.089
<i>I'm just not breathing.</i>

24:25.089 --> 24:27.508
<i>I'm trying to figure out</i>
<i>how to keep it together,</i>

24:27.508 --> 24:31.428
and I want Ben to swing as hard
as he can

24:31.428 --> 24:33.931
<i>to make up for the lightness</i>
<i>of my blade.</i>

24:34.932 --> 24:38.018
<i>[hard rock music]</i>

24:38.018 --> 24:45.109
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:45.109 --> 24:47.319
Oh, my gosh.

24:47.319 --> 24:50.197
- Well, Brad, I really like
the construction of your handle.

24:50.197 --> 24:52.408
It was comfortable in my hand
when I was swinging it.

24:52.408 --> 24:54.284
The blade is still straight,

24:54.284 --> 24:56.704
but there is a little fold
right there,

24:56.704 --> 24:58.080
but the rest of it went well.

24:58.080 --> 24:59.790
Nice job.

24:59.790 --> 25:00.958
Brendan, are you ready?

25:00.958 --> 25:02.626
- Sure.

25:02.626 --> 25:04.294
- You sound very sure
of yourself.

25:05.713 --> 25:07.506
<i>- I don't think I've ever been</i>
<i>more anxious for somebody</i>

25:07.506 --> 25:10.300
<i>to chop a hoof in half.</i>

25:10.300 --> 25:12.511
I really hope
that forge weld holds.

25:14.179 --> 25:21.145
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:27.526 --> 25:30.404
- Well, Brendan, I like
the forward heaviness of this

25:30.404 --> 25:32.656
for a chopping blade,

25:32.656 --> 25:34.408
but this thing's all about what
the hooves do to your knife,

25:34.408 --> 25:37.327
and they kicked it
in the knife right here.

25:37.327 --> 25:40.456
There's some pretty
significant chipping.

25:40.456 --> 25:43.208
The other issue I have
is the handle is really small

25:43.208 --> 25:45.669
and kind of hard to hold on to.

25:45.669 --> 25:47.463
Jeff, are you ready?

25:47.463 --> 25:49.256
- I've been waiting
four seasons. I'm ready.

25:49.256 --> 25:50.549
- You've been waiting
at the Four Seasons?

25:50.549 --> 25:51.508
That's nice.

25:51.508 --> 25:53.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:53.719 --> 25:56.180
<i>- I'm extremely nervous</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

25:56.180 --> 25:58.932
<i>I can see the chips</i>
<i>in Brendan's blade.</i>

25:58.932 --> 26:00.142
Mine could easily
do the same thing.

26:01.351 --> 26:02.895
[exhales sharply]

26:02.895 --> 26:09.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:13.906 --> 26:16.492
- Well, Jeff, this is
a heck of a chopper.

26:16.492 --> 26:19.244
It's like your knife
didn't even see the hooves.

26:19.244 --> 26:22.081
The one criticism I have about
this blade is that the handle

26:22.081 --> 26:23.791
is about an inch too long.

26:23.791 --> 26:25.042
It doesn't have a really
comfortable place to sit

26:25.042 --> 26:27.086
and be held,

26:27.086 --> 26:28.170
but very well done.
Nice blade.

26:28.170 --> 26:29.129
- Thank you.

26:30.255 --> 26:32.549
- All right, gentlemen.

26:32.549 --> 26:34.718
This is the sharpness test, and
what I want to see in this test

26:34.718 --> 26:38.347
is a nice clean cut without
any snags or tears in the bag.

26:38.347 --> 26:39.348
Brad, you're up first.
You ready?

26:39.348 --> 26:41.183
- I'm ready.

26:41.183 --> 26:48.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:53.570 --> 26:56.657
Ooh.

26:56.657 --> 26:58.325
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:58.325 --> 27:01.036
- You can see the cuts
are pretty clean.

27:01.036 --> 27:02.329
I mean, there's that nick there,
but I don't think

27:02.329 --> 27:03.997
it grabbed anything.

27:03.997 --> 27:06.583
It's a cutter.
It's sharp. Good job.

27:06.583 --> 27:07.918
All right, Brendan,
you're up.

27:07.918 --> 27:10.546
You ready?
- Ready to go.

27:10.546 --> 27:13.173
<i>Even though my blade's got a</i>
<i>big old bite taken out of it,</i>

27:13.173 --> 27:15.175
<i>I'm still hoping</i>
<i>that the remainder,</i>

27:15.175 --> 27:17.177
what little there is,
of the blade,

27:17.177 --> 27:20.305
will actually slice.

27:20.305 --> 27:23.559
If it doesn't go right,
that's it. I'm going home.

27:23.559 --> 27:24.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:40.701 --> 27:42.995
- Those chips and dings
in your blade--you can see

27:42.995 --> 27:45.539
there's a lot of material
just hung up on them.

27:45.539 --> 27:48.500
I mean, the edge is sharp
on either side of that,

27:48.500 --> 27:50.627
but with those missing
places in there,

27:50.627 --> 27:53.088
it kind of caught
and pulled through.

27:53.088 --> 27:56.091
It will cut, but it also tears.

27:56.091 --> 27:58.010
All right, Jeff, are you ready?

27:58.010 --> 27:59.011
- I'm ready.

27:59.011 --> 28:05.976
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:12.733 --> 28:15.569
- So Jeff, you've got a really,
really stout edge on there,

28:15.569 --> 28:18.196
but there wasn't any resistance
when I made those cuts.

28:18.196 --> 28:19.740
It really just passed
right through.

28:19.740 --> 28:21.325
The bag speaks for itself.

28:21.325 --> 28:22.534
It's a cutter. Nicely done.

28:22.534 --> 28:24.286
- Thank you.

28:24.286 --> 28:26.413
- Bladesmiths,

28:26.413 --> 28:28.165
the judges have completed
the deliberation,

28:28.165 --> 28:29.917
and they've made
a final decision.

28:29.917 --> 28:31.835
It's time for one of you
to leave the Forge.

28:31.835 --> 28:35.255
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:35.255 --> 28:38.759
Brendan, your blade
did not make the cut.

28:38.759 --> 28:40.719
Doug Marcaida will explain.

28:40.719 --> 28:42.930
- Brendan, I commend you
for staying in the game,

28:42.930 --> 28:45.015
but as you can see,

28:45.015 --> 28:47.434
your blade took the most damage
during the strength test.

28:47.434 --> 28:50.187
The process that you did to
harden and sharpen your blade

28:50.187 --> 28:52.064
made your edge brittle,

28:52.064 --> 28:55.108
and for that reason,
we have to let you go.

28:55.108 --> 28:57.736
- Brendan, please surrender
your weapon.

28:57.736 --> 28:59.404
- I'm bummed out that
I don't get to make

28:59.404 --> 29:01.114
the historical weapon,

29:01.114 --> 29:04.326
<i>but this was</i>
<i>a fantastic opportunity.</i>

29:04.326 --> 29:06.995
I'm out of the way,
Brad and Jeff.

29:06.995 --> 29:10.123
<i>May the best man win,</i>
<i>and good luck.</i>

29:12.793 --> 29:14.962
- Brad, Jeff, congratulations.

29:14.962 --> 29:17.047
You've made it to the final
round of this competition.

29:17.047 --> 29:19.508
Now we're gonna send
you home for five days

29:19.508 --> 29:22.302
to recreate an iconic weapon
from history.

29:22.302 --> 29:23.595
That weapon is...

29:23.595 --> 29:26.056
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:26.056 --> 29:28.767
the schiavona.

29:28.767 --> 29:30.352
<i>Rising to popularity in Italy</i>

29:30.352 --> 29:32.688
<i>during the 16th and 17th</i>
<i>centuries,</i>

29:32.688 --> 29:35.273
<i>the schiavona became the</i>
<i>trusted weapon for mercenaries</i>

29:35.273 --> 29:37.734
<i>recruited to guard</i>
<i>the Venetian head of state.</i>

29:37.734 --> 29:39.903
<i>The sword's long blade</i>
<i>included multiple fullers</i>

29:39.903 --> 29:42.072
<i>to lighten its weight,</i>
<i>while its straight double edge</i>

29:42.072 --> 29:44.908
<i>made it conducive for</i>
<i>deadly thrusts and cuts.</i>

29:44.908 --> 29:46.952
<i>The most eye-catching</i>
<i>feature of this blade</i>

29:46.952 --> 29:49.287
<i>was its basket hilt</i>
<i>with multiple pieces of steel</i>

29:49.287 --> 29:52.457
<i>that intertwined to protect</i>
<i>the hand from brutal slashes.</i>

29:52.457 --> 29:54.292
<i>Its attractive</i>
<i>yet deadly qualities</i>

29:54.292 --> 29:56.545
<i>are why the schiavona</i>
<i>can still be found today</i>

29:56.545 --> 29:59.923
<i>in popular games such</i>
<i>as "Assassin's Creed."</i>

29:59.923 --> 30:02.509
Your schiavona must include
a traditional basket

30:02.509 --> 30:04.386
guard and hilt,

30:04.386 --> 30:07.639
and to top it all off,
a cat's head pommel.

30:07.639 --> 30:09.850
At the end of five days,

30:09.850 --> 30:11.518
you'll return and present
your schiavonas

30:11.518 --> 30:12.644
to our panel of expert
judges to determine

30:12.644 --> 30:14.187
which of you deserves to be

30:14.187 --> 30:16.064
the next
"Forged in Fire" champion,

30:16.064 --> 30:18.650
who also earns $10,000.

30:18.650 --> 30:21.236
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

30:24.322 --> 30:27.492
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:27.492 --> 30:29.745
<i>- To get to the third stage</i>
<i>and to be at home</i>

30:29.745 --> 30:32.456
<i>in my element--</i>
<i>I'm feeling awesome.</i>

30:32.456 --> 30:35.500
Apparently an Italian sword.
Absolutely beautiful.

30:35.500 --> 30:38.628
Hopefully mine ends up
just as beautiful.

30:38.628 --> 30:40.589
Try to get my 5160 heated up

30:40.589 --> 30:43.967
so I can get some kind
of a profile going.

30:43.967 --> 30:45.969
<i>This sword's gonna be</i>
<i>hard enough to build,</i>

30:45.969 --> 30:49.514
but the handle is--I'd say
damn near impossible,

30:49.514 --> 30:53.101
<i>but I'm here for a reason,</i>
<i>and the reason is to win it.</i>

30:55.145 --> 30:58.315
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:58.315 --> 31:00.233
<i>- It's gonna be</i>
<i>quite a challenge.</i>

31:00.233 --> 31:02.486
<i>There's so many things</i>
<i>that have to be done.</i>

31:02.486 --> 31:06.239
<i>There's the blade, there's the</i>
<i>hilt, there's the cross guard.</i>

31:06.239 --> 31:08.450
I'm really nervous.

31:08.450 --> 31:12.662
The first thing I want to do
is get the blade hammered out.

31:12.662 --> 31:18.543
The blade is down to less than
1/4 inch thick, so that's good.

31:18.543 --> 31:20.462
<i>I usually work</i>
<i>with a lot of energy,</i>

31:20.462 --> 31:22.756
<i>and I need to let it out.</i>

31:22.756 --> 31:29.721
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:33.350 --> 31:35.268
That's so hard.

31:35.268 --> 31:36.228
[laughs]

31:37.854 --> 31:40.148
- My profile is finished.

31:40.148 --> 31:45.612
I'm not ready to get to the
grinder, but it has to be done.

31:45.612 --> 31:49.116
<i>Right now, it's looking good.</i>

31:49.116 --> 31:50.951
<i>My biggest fear right now</i>

31:50.951 --> 31:52.661
<i>is if I don't get</i>
<i>my heat treat right</i>

31:52.661 --> 31:54.913
<i>and I start getting</i>
<i>a big warp in it,</i>

31:54.913 --> 31:57.707
I'll be running around like
a chicken with my head cut off.

31:57.707 --> 32:04.631
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:11.847 --> 32:15.767
[bleep] big warp.

32:15.767 --> 32:17.477
I'm about ready to start

32:17.477 --> 32:19.688
breaking everything
I could find.

32:19.688 --> 32:21.356
I'm gonna freak out.
Son of a [bleep].

32:21.356 --> 32:22.691
[bleep] damn it.

32:25.902 --> 32:29.114
<i>I have to find a way to</i>
<i>straighten my blade somehow.</i>

32:29.114 --> 32:32.659
So I put it up on my 2x4s,
and tried to do a counter bend.

32:32.659 --> 32:35.370
If this does not work,
I am screwed.

32:35.370 --> 32:36.913
<i>I'm gonna have to present</i>
<i>a blade</i>

32:36.913 --> 32:38.331
<i>with a slight warp in it.</i>

32:40.542 --> 32:43.920
<i>- Today, the first thing</i>
<i>I want to do is to heat treat.</i>

32:43.920 --> 32:46.381
Come on, baby.

32:46.381 --> 32:49.634
The blade is about
40 inches long,

32:49.634 --> 32:51.720
<i>so I'm just hoping</i>
<i>that it's not gonna bend.</i>

32:54.890 --> 32:56.600
I wonder how often they're bent.

32:56.600 --> 33:03.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:03.064 --> 33:05.442
It's straighter
than when I put it in.

33:05.442 --> 33:07.152
I'm so excited.

33:07.152 --> 33:10.739
<i>Now I can focus</i>
<i>on making the hilt.</i>

33:10.739 --> 33:13.658
<i>This hilt has a lot</i>
<i>of pieces involved.</i>

33:13.658 --> 33:15.702
This is so much fun, though.

33:15.702 --> 33:19.456
<i>So my biggest issue</i>
<i>I'm worried about is time.</i>

33:19.456 --> 33:23.960
<i>I hope it goes well.</i>
My hand's shaking.

33:23.960 --> 33:26.129
- Looks like I got the bend out.

33:26.129 --> 33:28.006
<i>Now I can specialize</i>
<i>on that handle,</i>

33:28.006 --> 33:31.092
<i>and the guard,</i>
<i>and just make it immaculate.</i>

33:31.092 --> 33:33.136
This is homemade Micarta.

33:33.136 --> 33:34.930
It should be a lot stronger
than wood.

33:34.930 --> 33:37.390
<i>I plan on wrapping it</i>
<i>with leather.</i>

33:37.390 --> 33:40.602
<i>The guard's gonna be tough.</i>

33:40.602 --> 33:42.854
<i>I'm learning as I go.</i>

33:42.854 --> 33:44.272
<i>Seems like a lot</i>
<i>of the competition's</i>

33:44.272 --> 33:46.024
<i>lately been really been close,</i>

33:46.024 --> 33:49.819
<i>so it's just down</i>
<i>to fit and finish.</i>

33:49.819 --> 33:52.781
It feels pretty damn good.

33:52.781 --> 33:54.574
I just want to see
if it'll cut through rope.

33:55.784 --> 34:00.497
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:00.497 --> 34:03.458
Well, it worked on
that little one.

34:03.458 --> 34:06.253
My guard ended up rubbing
on my knuckles quite a bit.

34:06.253 --> 34:08.338
<i>I don't have no time</i>
<i>to fix it,</i>

34:08.338 --> 34:10.257
so hopefully it doesn't rub
the judges like it rubbed me,

34:10.257 --> 34:11.633
but we're gonna see.

34:11.633 --> 34:14.803
I am excited to see it compete.

34:14.803 --> 34:16.805
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:16.805 --> 34:19.432
- This is hickory,
or in Connecticut, "hickoreh,"

34:19.432 --> 34:21.977
or from where I'm from,
"hickoreh."

34:21.977 --> 34:24.813
<i>Today, I'm gonna get</i>
<i>the handle finished.</i>

34:24.813 --> 34:27.315
<i>I'm gonna use the old</i>
<i>Italian riding boots</i>

34:27.315 --> 34:30.193
<i>and wrap the handle</i>
<i>with some leather,</i>

34:30.193 --> 34:32.445
<i>then get everything</i>
<i>fitted together properly.</i>

34:32.445 --> 34:36.408
This is [bleep] crazy looking.

34:36.408 --> 34:39.077
At this point, I'm gonna do
some very gentle testing on it.

34:39.077 --> 34:41.329
<i>I have so much time and effort</i>

34:41.329 --> 34:44.124
<i>just into getting the right</i>
<i>hardness and springiness</i>

34:44.124 --> 34:46.918
to this blade that I really
don't want to mess it up.

34:46.918 --> 34:49.212
<i>I'll leave that</i>
<i>for the judges to do.</i>

34:49.212 --> 34:51.589
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:51.589 --> 34:53.550
That was outstanding.

34:53.550 --> 34:55.677
Let's hear it for Friggy.

34:56.761 --> 34:59.639
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:59.639 --> 35:02.767
- Brad, Jeff,
welcome back to the Forge.

35:02.767 --> 35:04.644
Brad, tell us about your blade.

35:04.644 --> 35:07.063
- I have fallen totally
in love with my blade.

35:09.190 --> 35:11.151
<i>The biggest thing</i>
<i>I'm worried about</i>

35:11.151 --> 35:13.445
<i>is getting beat by a linesman.</i>

35:13.445 --> 35:15.405
[laughter]

35:15.405 --> 35:16.615
- So, Jeff, tell us
about your blade.

35:16.615 --> 35:18.742
- I'm usually my worst critic,

35:18.742 --> 35:21.786
<i>so I'm just gonna say</i>
<i>it's one bad-ass blade.</i>

35:21.786 --> 35:26.124
I love it. I can't wait
to see it kill something.

35:26.124 --> 35:27.292
- All right, gentlemen.
Up next is our weapons test.

35:27.292 --> 35:29.919
Up first, the kill test.

35:29.919 --> 35:30.920
Doug?

35:31.630 --> 35:33.840
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:33.840 --> 35:36.009
- Well, Brad, as you can see,

35:36.009 --> 35:37.469
I'm still recovering
from an injury,

35:37.469 --> 35:39.387
so to be my arm today

35:39.387 --> 35:41.890
and to have the pleasure
of testing your weapon,

35:41.890 --> 35:44.684
I'd like to bring back
one of my favorite students:

35:44.684 --> 35:47.062
my brother, R. J. Marcaida.

35:47.062 --> 35:50.106
<i>- I think my sword is a lot</i>
<i>prettier than Jeff's,</i>

35:50.106 --> 35:52.901
so I'm not really worrying
about the aesthetics.

35:52.901 --> 35:53.943
<i>I'm worried about</i>
<i>the sharpness.</i>

35:57.656 --> 36:04.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:13.380 --> 36:14.464
- [inaudible].

36:16.383 --> 36:18.176
All right, Brad.

36:18.176 --> 36:19.928
The one issue I have
about your handle

36:19.928 --> 36:23.223
right here--it did cause
some issues by rubbing

36:23.223 --> 36:25.725
against the thumb right there.

36:25.725 --> 36:27.686
But more importantly,

36:27.686 --> 36:30.438
it is a sharp blade
for slashing and thrusting.

36:30.438 --> 36:32.107
It will kill.

36:32.107 --> 36:34.359
- Cool.
- Jeff, you ready?

36:34.359 --> 36:37.362
- Let's do this.
You know, it's a good thing

36:37.362 --> 36:38.905
<i>that they said something</i>
<i>about Brad's handle,</i>

36:38.905 --> 36:40.615
because I know that
he's gonna be saying

36:40.615 --> 36:42.659
<i>the same thing about mine.</i>

36:42.659 --> 36:44.411
<i>I'm just praying to God</i>

36:44.411 --> 36:46.287
<i>that it cuts this thing</i>
<i>right in half,</i>

36:46.287 --> 36:47.122
because that's the only thing
that's gonna save me

36:47.122 --> 36:48.081
at this point.

36:50.875 --> 36:57.799
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:04.889 --> 37:07.934
Ooh.

37:07.934 --> 37:09.185
- One right here.

37:09.185 --> 37:10.311
Okay.

37:10.311 --> 37:12.522
All right, Jeff.

37:12.522 --> 37:14.941
The little bit on the inside
of your basket hilt right there,

37:14.941 --> 37:18.653
it did dig in into his knuckles.

37:18.653 --> 37:20.822
But overall,

37:20.822 --> 37:22.824
if we're talking about a killing
blade here with good balance

37:22.824 --> 37:26.286
and the kind of destruction
it did, it will kill.

37:26.286 --> 37:29.038
- Thank you.
- Good job.

37:29.038 --> 37:31.583
All right, bladesmiths.
Next up is the strength test.

37:31.583 --> 37:32.876
Ben?

37:34.711 --> 37:37.297
- To test your schiavona's
basket and blade,

37:37.297 --> 37:39.424
I'm gonna punch into
these terra cotta pots

37:39.424 --> 37:41.426
and then chop
into these birch logs.

37:41.426 --> 37:43.720
Now, remember, it's not what
happens to the vase or the wood;

37:43.720 --> 37:45.805
it's what happens to your blade.

37:45.805 --> 37:47.640
Brad, you're up first.
You ready?

37:47.640 --> 37:49.225
- My schiavona's
definitely ready.

37:51.394 --> 37:58.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:10.205 --> 38:13.082
- [laughs]

38:13.082 --> 38:14.709
- Well, Brad,

38:14.709 --> 38:16.294
once I started chopping
into that log,

38:16.294 --> 38:18.087
it was just going
the whole time.

38:18.087 --> 38:20.298
There is a tiny little
deformation right there.

38:20.298 --> 38:23.051
It's pretty narrow.

38:23.051 --> 38:24.886
You can hear it, you know?

38:24.886 --> 38:27.055
All in all, it's sharp,
and it's a good chopper.

38:27.055 --> 38:29.224
Nicely done.
- Thank you.

38:29.224 --> 38:30.809
- All right, Jeff. You're up.
You ready?

38:30.809 --> 38:32.727
- Let's do this.

38:32.727 --> 38:34.604
<i>I'm not too worried</i>
<i>about the handle.</i>

38:34.604 --> 38:36.731
Maybe it might hurt his hand
if he's punching into it,

38:36.731 --> 38:39.150
but I'm more worried
about that edge curling.

38:41.861 --> 38:48.785
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:55.041 --> 38:57.544
- Nice.

38:57.544 --> 39:00.046
- Well, Jeff,
this is a heck of a chopper.

39:00.046 --> 39:02.131
It's got a lot
of forward weight.

39:02.131 --> 39:04.676
It's a little bit on the
heavy side, but not too much.

39:04.676 --> 39:07.720
In general, and in total,
it held up very well.

39:07.720 --> 39:09.138
Nice job.
- Thank you.

39:11.599 --> 39:13.601
- All right, gentlemen.

39:13.601 --> 39:16.437
This is our sharpness test:
a rope and sandbag slash.

39:16.437 --> 39:19.566
What I'll do to test the edges
of your blade is slice the rope,

39:19.566 --> 39:21.985
releasing the sandbag,
then cut the bag.

39:21.985 --> 39:24.028
What we want to see are good,
clean cuts through the rope

39:24.028 --> 39:25.989
and clean cuts through the bag.

39:25.989 --> 39:27.198
Brad, you're up first.
You ready?

39:27.198 --> 39:28.157
- Ready.

39:31.452 --> 39:38.376
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:44.883 --> 39:46.134
- Oh!

39:46.134 --> 39:48.303
[both chuckle]

39:48.303 --> 39:50.305
- Okay, Brad.

39:50.305 --> 39:52.974
On the cuts, passed through
the rope with no problem.

39:52.974 --> 39:55.018
This blade has a beautiful edge.

39:55.018 --> 39:56.853
A fine cutter.
Excellent. Well done.

39:56.853 --> 39:59.439
- Thank you.
- Jeff, you ready?

39:59.439 --> 40:01.357
- Let's get it on.
- All right. Let's do this.

40:01.357 --> 40:04.319
<i>- I think right now</i>
<i>we're almost dead even.</i>

40:04.319 --> 40:07.113
<i>Couldn't be any closer.</i>

40:07.113 --> 40:09.616
If I don't drop one cleanly
in half like he did,

40:09.616 --> 40:11.075
<i>it's not good.</i>

40:14.412 --> 40:21.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:29.844 --> 40:31.179
Oh.

40:32.472 --> 40:34.098
- All right, Jeff, what I like
about your blade

40:34.098 --> 40:36.476
is its look--
this industrial look.

40:36.476 --> 40:38.311
It's cool.

40:38.311 --> 40:39.771
It didn't slice all the way
through the bag,

40:39.771 --> 40:42.523
but it cuts very cleanly.
Nicely done.

40:42.523 --> 40:45.276
- Thank you.

40:45.276 --> 40:47.153
- Brad, Jeff,

40:47.153 --> 40:49.614
you are both extraordinary
weapon smiths,

40:49.614 --> 40:52.200
but there can only be one
"Forged in Fire" champion.

40:52.200 --> 40:55.912
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:55.912 --> 40:57.956
Jeff, congratulations.

40:57.956 --> 41:01.209
You are our newest
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:01.209 --> 41:03.878
Brad, unfortunately, your weapon
did not make the cut.

41:03.878 --> 41:07.215
- Brad, this is probably
the most difficult hilt design

41:07.215 --> 41:09.926
we have sent any
of our smiths home to do,

41:09.926 --> 41:11.594
and you both did
a really nice job,

41:11.594 --> 41:14.097
and we had to look
at the finest of details,

41:14.097 --> 41:17.517
and that was that rolled edge
you took in the strength test,

41:17.517 --> 41:20.603
and that's why we've
got to send you home.

41:20.603 --> 41:23.064
- Brad, please surrender
your weapon.

41:23.064 --> 41:25.692
<i>- I did the best that I could,</i>

41:25.692 --> 41:28.403
and I put every single bit
of effort into my blade,

41:28.403 --> 41:31.572
<i>and Jeff, I hope</i>
<i>we become friends forever.</i>

41:31.572 --> 41:34.200
I definitely have a lot
to learn from you,

41:34.200 --> 41:37.787
and I was just so close
to being the champion.

41:37.787 --> 41:41.040
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:41.040 --> 41:44.168
- Jeff, you are the new
"Forged in Fire" champion

41:44.168 --> 41:47.672
and will be receiving a check
for $10,000.

41:47.672 --> 41:49.257
How do you feel?

41:49.257 --> 41:50.550
- My heart's pounding
out of my chest.

41:50.550 --> 41:52.385
This is what I came here to do.

41:52.385 --> 41:54.595
- Please present your weapon
to the judges.

41:54.595 --> 41:56.806
- I feel fricking awesome.

41:56.806 --> 42:00.351
<i>This is everything.</i>
<i>This is what I wanted.</i>

42:00.351 --> 42:02.353
It's perfect.

42:02.353 --> 42:04.313
I heard Brendan might have
called me "Magic Mike,"

42:04.313 --> 42:06.315
but I'll tell you what,
the magic is floating, baby.

42:06.315 --> 42:07.984
The magic is floating.

42:07.984 --> 42:12.905
<i>♪ ♪</i>
